    q: "My DCS grill has uneven heat — one zone is much weaker. What's wrong?",
    a: "9 times out of 10 it's a ceramic radiant rod cracked or shattered between the burner and the cooking grate. The rods (OEM 245398, 9.5 inch) distribute heat evenly across the burner. When one breaks, that zone gets uneven hot spots and weaker overall heat. $40 to $60 part per rod, 30-minute repair if it's just one or two rods.",
  },
  {
    q: "How long do DCS grills last?",
    a: "With proper maintenance, 12 to 15 years on inland installs is typical. Coastal installs (Malibu, Newport Beach), 10 to 13 years before salt-driven U-burner pinhole becomes the limiting factor. Cooking grates and burners have lifetime warranties on the original purchaser. Ceramic radiants are wear items, plan to replace 4 to 6 of them at year 8 to 10.",
  },
  {
    q: "My DCS won't ignite at all. Where do I check first?",
    a: "DCS uses 120VAC mains power for ignition (different from Lynx and Sedona which use a 9V battery). If the grill is completely dead, check the outdoor GFCI receptacle. They trip from water intrusion in winter and stay tripped. Reset, retest. If that's not it, the next check is the wire harness from the receptacle to the control panel.",
  },
  {
    q: "Are the ceramic rod packs really sold in 10-packs?",
    a: "Yes. Fisher & Paykel OEM ships ceramic rods (245398) in packs of 10. Most BGB36 grills have 6 rods total, BGB48 grills have 8. For most repair scenarios we use 1 to 4 rods. If you have a full failure across all zones at year 12 to 14, the full pack makes sense and gives you spares for the next round.",
  },
  {
    q: "Do you process DCS lifetime warranty for me?",
    a: "Yes, when applicable. Many DCS components have lifetime warranty (cooking grates, burners on original purchaser, stainless construction). We document the failure, you call Fisher & Paykel customer care (1-888-936-7872), they ship the part, we install. You pay for labor only.",
